<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-187-032  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 187 032.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  March 1990 v7 n3 p70(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The performance measurement contest. (benchmark testing) (includesa related article on evaluating published benchmarks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Southerton, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hardware benchmarks are in great demand in the computer industry,yet benchmarks for Unix are lacking in many respects.andO;Fortunately, a number of new benchmarks are emerging.andP;  The SystemsPerformance Evaluation Committee (SPEC), a consortium of systemsmakers, is devising benchmark tests for workstations.andP;  Multiusersystems can be evaluated using a Remote Terminal Emulationbenchmark, which measures system performance against an acceptableresponse time using commercial applications.andP;  Synthetic benchmarkscombine raw performance testing with real-life testing, relying onthe benchmark software to simulate real-life conditions.andP;  Whatevertype of benchmark is chosen, it should provide information thatassists the user in making a purchase decision and brings plainlyto light an inferior product.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BenchmarksUNIXTestingPerformance MeasurementSystems Performance Evaluation Cooperative.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>